SIMPLE: ridge
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ridge
<hw>Ridge</hw> <pr>(r⟦icr⟧j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>rigge</ets> the back, AS. <ets>hrycg</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>rug</ets>, G. <ets>r⟦uum⟧cken</ets>, OHG. <ets>rucki</ets>,
<ets>hrukki</ets>, Icel. <ets>hryggr</ets>, Sw. <ets>rugg</ets>, Dan.
<ets>ryg</ets>. ⟦root⟧16.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The back, or top of
the back; a crest.</def> <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A range of hills or mountains, or the upper part of
such a range; any extended elevation between valleys.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
frozen <xex>ridges</xex> of the Alps.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Part rise in crystal wall, or <qex>ridge</qex> direct.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A raised line or strip, as of ground thrown up by a
plow or left between furrows or ditches, or as on the surface of metal,
cloth, or bone, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The intersection of two surface
forming a salient angle, especially the angle at the top between the
opposite slopes or sides of a roof or a vault.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>The highest portion of the glacis
proceeding from the salient angle of the covered way.</def>
<rj><au>Stocqueler.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ridge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ridge
<hw>Ridge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ridged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ridging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form a ridge of;
to furnish with a ridge or ridges; to make into a ridge or
ridges.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bristles ranged like those that <qex>ridge</qex> the back⟦br⟧
Of chafed wild boars.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form into ridges with the plow, as
land.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wrinkle.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With a forehead
<xex>ridged</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ridgeband</ent>⟦br⟧
